text: @Kit_Yates_Maths Yikes 😳
@MichelleW1601 @suzi_k123 @Neesh_bloggs @SGriffin_Lab Much appreciated, thank you!
@alisonleary1 @HPIAndyCowper Heaven help us all. Please tell me this isn’t real.

@essexsarahlee What on earth? Were Black, Acheson, Whitehead & Marmot politically motivated as well? That’s going to make an awfully big elephant in the room this winter as we deal knock-on effect on health of the winter fuel hikes when the NHS has been on winter footing all summer.

@essexsarahlee @CharleyBaker1 If they don’t, retention will drop and HEIs will lose money - & so will the NHS where Apprenticeships are concerned because of the link to the levy. And then, you know, staffing, patient safety, patient care… Nobody wins.
@Katynurse27 @irnbrufan @alisonleary1 Amazing how everyone else always knows better than the person who’s actually IN post 😉

@alisonleary1 I recall having a ‘spirited discussion’ with someone once who was adamant that an NQN B5 had a starting graduate salary of £30,000. I asked him on what planet! This does nursing no favours & it feeds public misperceptions. A quick search on NHS Jobs gives a much fairer view.

@trishgreenhalgh I think every time if we’d locked down sooner it could have been shorter. The space they provided wasn’t utilised & exit strategies were poor. Public health messages were confused at best. A multi-faceted approach would have reduced the need for them with time as well.

@BlondeHistorian This is awful. When you have the energy to do so, please complain. This is common assault. Many elements of this go against the NMC code of conduct & have no justification. It needs to stop. I hope during the rest of your pregnancy you have a better experience.
@alisonleary1 Yep - and this is the result 🤦🏼‍♀️

@alisonleary1 So sad. I saw a basic lack of empathy & no evidence-based rationale for decisions made (eg removing the guide dog). Reads as a control/power play. We need to do more to proactively screen for this than employ the unsuitable out of desperation. Not every nurse should nurse.

@alisonleary1 For staff buy-in it needs to reduce as it switches, not just transfer. Also needs to consolidate IT skills with training for staff who will inevitably have to learn more IT. And please, PLEASE don’t forget Paeds! One size really doesn’t fit all!

@alisonleary1 The digital step is quite capable of creating A. LOT. of extra work if not done in full collaboration with frontline staff. Needs to be a step-by-step process that evaluates as it goes. Have known some really awful (work-creating) gaffs when this hasn’t been done right.
@fascinatorfun …good grief 😳😵‍💫

@StN_Freda Just lean into your strengths. Plenty of roles out there combine theory with patient care, but your solid evidence base will inform your practice regardless & you can definitely use it to your patients’ & your own advantage. Good for you - enjoy your next block!
@JudithM06504029 @alisonleary1 Multiple ones, apparently 😳🤔😂
@alisonleary1 That was my new word for the day! 😂
@alisonleary1 Got sent this absolute beaut on Facebook the other day after tagging a friend on a post that had… nothing to do with flowers 😂 Made both our days 😂 https://t.co/bavY9LXAG1

@alisonleary1 @tadhg50 @kellyMcgovern21 @MSEHospitals It figures. Practice Education leads are another role I’ve seen downgraded to a 6 instead of a 7. Trusts won’t retain staff if they don’t pay them what they’re worth. Lack of competition from other Trusts offering a higher band won’t stop them haemorrhaging staff.
@reboverend_RNc @JaneEBall Thanks. It’s easily overlooked. I know I’m certainly guilty of it at times.

@JaneEBall I’ve been helped immensely by so many of the tweets by people on this thread that have helped me to reflect & participate in professional discussions that have expanded my thinking. I’m grateful for all of them. Perhaps we don’t feed back & say thankyou as often as we should.
@SpreadSmile13 @jade_w08 @ldivaf @WeStudentNurse @StNurseProject @theRCN @RCNNRN Good resource! Thanks 👍

@jade_w08 @ldivaf @WeStudentNurse @StNurseProject @theRCN @RCNNRN I think most courses are very similar in that regard but it still piles on stress for those less able, including older adult learners with competing priorities, undiagnosed dyscalculia, dyslexia etc. Study Hubs need to be better geared up to address/support these students.

@ldivaf @WeStudentNurse @StNurseProject @theRCN @RCNNRN False economy. Increasing enrolment is pointless if it increases chance of poor retention in Yr3 if/they can’t achieve 100% in their drug calcs. The minimum GCSE standard doesn’t remove that totally but it’s an extra layer to ensure ability. Not perfect but better than nothing.

@jade_w08 @ldivaf @WeStudentNurse @StNurseProject @theRCN @RCNNRN But if students are less able at maths they’ll struggle to get 100%, need more tries & at more risk of drop-out risk late in Year 3 - unfair to students & their mental health & wastes money/resources. The GCSE grade ensures a basic standard re: ability.
@credland_nicki Thankyou for sharing & for speaking out over this. Narratives like this are so important right now.

@alisonleary1 And more could be done to value & retain those roles as well. A good ward will move mountains to keep a solid housekeeper & ward clerk but again, upper management don’t always value their roles - which could be supported & made much more meaningful than they sometimes are.

@alisonleary1 @trewvs @JoThomasRN Which again comes back to the central post. Needs can’t be met if highly knowledgeable, skilled senior staff are pulled away from patient care (whatever form that takes) to fulfil HCA-level tasks. It’s a management/planning issue that centres around poor role understanding.

@GinaFree3 @alisonleary1 @Torig1983 And this is exactly it: uninformed opinions based on the failure to understand each other’s roles. When these result in management decisions, everyone suffers - primarily, patients. Academia is not an ivory tower. CNSs don’t do less work because they aren’t on the ward 24/7.

@jneill @MichaelYeadon3 @ClareCraigPath @Stat_O_Guy @FatEmperor @RealJoelSmalley Feels like a giant rolling car crash now - that’s the damage these voices have done (along with crap public health messaging) 😖

@alisonleary1 @JoThomasRN It’s interesting though - that nursing M/BScs might reduce perceived respect. Is that an idea of nurses ‘stepping out of their box’ - taking on care that was traditionally seen as part of the dr’s role? Interesting given how the acuity & complexity of patient care has changed.

@alisonleary1 @JoThomasRN @CloughleyS_GPN No one is putting anyone down here - it’s a discussion. Insights are being shared. Re: respect for nursing, Project 2000 did a lot of damage, but we learnt from it - things will continue to adapt but nursing degrees are thorough & robust to meet a different set of needs.
@jneill @MichaelYeadon3 @ClareCraigPath @Stat_O_Guy @FatEmperor @RealJoelSmalley Somehow I never saw this at the time. Wish I had. It’s great - and no less relevant now!

@caspertown42 @alisonleary1 @Michell26640168 The other assumption I’ve picked up in the past is that drs & CNSs are somehow interchangeable. I wonder if upper management share that view. However the consultants I’ve worked with in the past have been the first to say that the CNSs on the MDT are unique & invaluable.

@caspertown42 @alisonleary1 @Michell26640168 Plus drs cannot pick up the CNS caseload because the role is not the same & medicine is facing a very similar situation right now as well - pushing the issues (ie patient care) further ‘up the line’ resolves nothing & escalates situations that are already complex.
@alisonleary1 @caspertown42 @Michell26640168 None at all. It’s not even crisis management.

@caspertown42 @alisonleary1 @Michell26640168 …plus in the original example a lot of this is/can be part of the HCA role. Surely it’s more cost-effective to release more non-clinical HCA posts rather than pay a CNS to do it?

@caspertown42 @alisonleary1 @Michell26640168 It’s also about taking advantage of peoples’ innate good nature: who wouldn’t stop & give a quick hand to someone making a bed on their own? But that’s the CNS’s choice - not a patronising add-on to the JD that leaves a CNS’s own caseload backlogged/uncared for in the process.
@Charlie34895116 @TheFigen @Jopo_dr Thought you could add it to one of the Maths PPTs 😉
@TheFigen @Jopo_dr @Charlie34895116 here’s another way to do it! 😳😂

@alisonleary1 @LandDHospital @CNOEngland @MRadford_HEECN @NavinaEvans @BriceEm @patcullen9 @RCNEastern I’m so sick of this assumption that Specialist Nurses aren’t that busy because they aren’t on the ward. The opposite is true. When you pull an oncology nurse specialist out of clinic or off of home visits to scrub the sluice & restock the IVs, what happens to those patients? 🤦🏼‍♀️

@reboverend_RNc @alisonleary1 @HellewellKaren It’s a massive disparity - but it will take a big shift that many are not willing to make due to the impact on shifts, staffing etc - but if eg the children’s asthma specialist nurses had a weekly slot to update staff on inhaler/spacer technique, the diff it would make!

@reboverend_RNc @alisonleary1 @HellewellKaren Personally I think nursing itself needs restructuring similarly to medicine where teaching & learning are factored into the standard day/shift & are as integral as  handover. Wishful thinking I know but that alone would have a huge impact & would invest visibly in current staff.
@alisonleary1 I haven’t been watching, but is that a cover for poor debating skills (poor listening skills being a given)?

@rgriffinskill …anyone with a Care Certificate can take on that title, call themselves a Senior HCA & work independently when really they are a carer. Misleading to the public & other professionals. There needs to be a minimum training standard as a matter of public safety.

@rgriffinskill I think this needs to be decided on a national level, regulated, and the title then protected as we are rightly working on with the Nurse title. Not only is it confusing between organisations with HCAs, CSWs, HCSWs etc, the minimum level of training isn’t required everywhere &…

@alisonleary1 But of course, in reality we are expected to run on near-misses so we’re failing right out of the gate. The fact that nothing adverse happened doesn’t resolve it: the very fact it happened means something adverse has already occurred. Reminds me of the RaDonda Vaught case.
@alisonleary1 (Current, not competent 🤦🏼‍♀️)
@alisonleary1 That level of responsibility for £10/hr in the competent cost of living crisis? Are they having a laugh? Plus that’s the same salary for a carer being paid through direct payments.

@Roethorn_pb @juliehelm9 @Laracapybara @EllzSummary @alisonleary1 @damien_page I think that’s half the issue: that people look in on what we do, see a bunch of qual & unqual staff all doing (in their eyes) the same thing and say, “I could do that,” or “You don’t have a degree & are doing it better.” & only see one level of ‘doing’ & none of the complexity.

@Roethorn_pb @juliehelm9 @Laracapybara @EllzSummary @alisonleary1 @damien_page Qualifying that: RNCs teach parents complex skills like emergency trache changes, shunt care, BiPAP etc. They are very highly skilled - but aren’t nurses. As an HCA way back when, I ran an ECG clinic & taught myself to spot SVT & LBBB - but I didn’t know what I didn’t know.

@Roethorn_pb @juliehelm9 @Laracapybara @EllzSummary @alisonleary1 @damien_page Not just skills - that’s half the issue: anyone can learn a skill. It’s the wide- ranging underpinning knowledge that feeds into higher level thinking, appraising and deduction (& more) & emotional intelligence that’s crucial in all nursing levels/fields & drives patient safety.
@ShaunLintern Me too - & they always lasted a minimum of a week & always went to my chest. Now, I’ve had 1 cold since 2019. Feels fab. Public health measures work! ✅

@alisonleary1 @LlewellynMorga2 @damien_page @theRCN @nmcnews Nursing strikes me at times as being a bit like the animal that turns on its own tail - and its own young. Whether it’s a big organisation and small charities or a practice assessor and a student/apprentice, the underpinning attitude is the same.
@alisonleary1 @LlewellynMorga2 @damien_page Nursing has an ego. There are a lot of strong opinions out there but unsupported by any evidence and with no real long-range view.

@alisonleary1 @damien_page Why pick on nursing? A little bit of understanding about A) routes into nursing, B) why that degree is absolutely necessary and C) that NURSING. ISN’T. JUST. GLORIFIED. CARING. THAT. ANYONE. CAN. DO. wouldn’t go amiss. ‘Straight speaking’ doesn’t excuse ignorance. Rant over 😄

@alitwy @BucksHealthcare @Karenbonner88 @LCNMUK @ClareRayner6 @fearnley_k @trishgreenhalgh @ProfEmer Sorry to hear this & glad they apologised. I question how much of this is down to lack of staff awareness re: the difference between FFP2/3 and surgical masks in general. This needs stepping up, especially when U.K. public health guidance on C19 in general is so very poor.
@DrRJWebb @ShaunLintern Agreed.
@alisonleary1 @PostDocHV Yep. There’s more to that story and it was extremely concerning. Which is why I personally think domiciliary carers and HCAs should be a regulated workforce as well.

@PostDocHV @alisonleary1 Are they also self-employed? I once came across a so-called ‘Senior HCA’ who gave herself the title and was self-employed in the community with her own caseload. No appropriate quals. Still gives me the creeps remembering it.
@CM_7505 @LCNMUK @alitwy @NHSEngland Case transcript here: https://t.co/UQfvxgbDyu
@CM_7505 @LCNMUK @alitwy @NHSEngland This would appear to be a case worth keeping an eye on… https://t.co/qJvY1AFnfT
@PostDocHV The Edexcel unit specifications for BTEC H&SC Levels 2&3 should be available online. Also the Level 4&5 foundation degree. Used to teach on both. Not aware of any primary research though.

@MrsBosanquet @kennygibsonnhs Also, as a redeployed NQN, what have they actively done to support transition ie preceptorship? If this went to HR as it currently appears, the ward wouldn’t have a leg to stand on & it suggests pretty clear-cut bullying covered up by a toxic triad that needs proactive managing.

@MrsBosanquet @kennygibsonnhs If stress is a (very understandable) factor here then it sounds like it’s building on leadership & people management practices that were already poor. Lots of work done on the impact of belonging on patient safety, teamworking etc & self-aware leadership is key.

@CM_7505 @LCNMUK @alitwy @NHSEngland I’m assuming that this is the sticking point. Recognition of Long COVID as a disability by the courts I’m guessing is what would tie all of this together by the look of things? Apologies if I’m being a bit dense here. https://t.co/HOtNDl58RF

@CM_7505 @LCNMUK @alitwy @NHSEngland Thought I’d repost so those who know more can judge. My first thought was the potential duty of care breach in penalising staff sickness when COVID was contracted via poor PPE etc (alongside the HSE case against Burnley college) but I’m no expert.
@alitwy @NHSEngland @LCNMUK Alongside cases like this one as well. Granted it isn’t NHS but it’s not a great stretch to see how it could be applied in the light of PPE. https://t.co/hLrTHbAnfu

@alitwy @NHSEngland @LCNMUK I wonder what bearing, if any, this case might have on it - COVID played a recognised role. I’m sure it isn’t/won’t be the only one.

@alisonleary1 @robmarki @AdvClin @maxwele2 @ProfJuneG @vlcurrie @CraigDavidson85 @LeanneHPatrick @CalvinMoorley @theRCN @RCNEKentBranch @RCNMandLForum @bjgw @RCN_inclusion @RCNScot @RCNGtrGlasgow @FeministRCN @sexnotgenderNM @RCNWomensHealth @RCNStudents @RCNNRN @alitwy @EBNursingBMJ I think sometimes (as in, quite often) the uncomfortable questions are the ones that need asking the most. 💪

@alisonleary1 PR exercise. Means nothing changes unless they instigate actual work-friendly policies which require the usual nonexistent retention/investment focused paradigm shift in recognition that the majority of the workforce have periods/are pre/peri/post-menopausal.
@DC_PoliceDogs If all goes well with TPD Albert (and it certainly looks like it!)  you ever consider cross-breeding him with one of the German Shepherds?

@alisonleary1 @beckyemmins88 If we consider it as basic then we’re unlikely to understand either the theory or the evidence behind it. All nursing care should be intentional, because all of it matters and all of it is complex - we just perhaps take some aspects for granted (erroneously) more than others.
@AndFry6 @ClimateActionN8 @drgregkelly In the light of the last 2 years, I feel like ‘unprecedented’ might be a bit of a push.

@maxwele2 @LeanneHPatrick @nmcnews @theRCN and @gmcuk are we for real here? Codes of Conduct? Upholding public trust in the profession? This isn’t doing a whole lot for MDT working, is it? Nevermind encouraging retention of healthcare staff before they’ve even started…? #metoo

@alisonleary1 @MRadford_HEECN …plus, even in my HCA days I refused to be a de facto tea maker for the doctors. We all have arms, legs and brains. Even in the late 1990s it wasn’t 1940 😉 Stereotypes = 🗑
@alisonleary1 Having reread this twice and just picked my jaw up off the ground, I’m grateful to have read @MRadford_HEECN’s reply on the next tweet down. This is unbelievable on so many levels.

@GidMK Thank you. I teach Evidence Based Practice and introduce my students to how to appraise research - accessible threads like this are so useful to help them see the difference between good quality research and published crap in ways they can easily grasp.
